Activity 6: Targeting Specific Nodes and Managing Services

  1. Objectives:

    1. Individualize hosts

    2. Apply tags in selecting plays to run

    3. Managing Services from remote servers using playbooks

2. Discussion:


In this activity, we try to individualize hosts. For example, we donâ€™t want apache on all our servers, or maybe only one of our servers is a web server, or maybe we have different servers like database or file servers running different things on different categories of servers and that is what we are going to take a look at in this activity.


We also try to manage services that do not automatically run using the automations in playbook. For example, when we install web servers or httpd for CentOS, we notice that the service did not start automatically.


Requirement:

In this activity, you will need to create another Ubuntu VM and name it Server 3. Likewise, you need to activate the second adapter to a host-only adapter after the installations. Take note of the IP address of the Server 3. Make sure to use the command ssh-copy-id to copy the public key to Server 3. Verify if you can successfully SSH to Server 3.

Task 2: Using Tags in running playbooks

In this task, our goal is to add metadata to our plays so that we can only run the plays that we want to run, and not all the plays in our playbook.


  1. Edit the site.yml file. Add tags to the playbook. After the name, we can place the tags: name_of_tag. This is an arbitrary command, which means you can use any name for a tag.


Make sure to save the file and exit.

Reflections:

  1. What is the importance of putting our remote servers into groups?

    • It is important to to categorize servers into groups not only for organization purposes but also to improve efficient management and implement automation smoothly and easily.


  2. What is the importance of tags in playbooks?

    • Implementing tags in playbooks plays a crucial role in automating tasks in multiple servers especially when having different operating systems among those servers since it allows you to categorize and add constraints to which servers you will execute the task.


  3. Why do think some services need to be managed automatically in playbooks?

    • Instead of executing the services manually using the terminal playbooks plays a crucial role in managing multiple servers and has many advantages and automation is only the first, using a playbook increases consistency and efficiency since it is rolled out once and also enforces security compared to manual managing. Playbooks also serve as documentation for future references on the current configurations.

Conclusion:

- In this hands-on activity I have demonstrated implementing playbooks with the use of tags and categorizing remote servers into categories. I have implemented a playbook following the procedures and adding constraints called as tags and tasks will only be executed on the desired machines declared under the specific tags in the inventory file. This new skill and knowledge I have learned has widened my perspective on implementing updates and managing multiple machines using playbooks. using tags and categories in managing machines will hopefully used by me somewhere in the future as a soon to be system administrator.
